SIMPLE: mark
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mark
<hw>Mark</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A license of
reprisals. See <er>Marque</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mark
<hw>Mark</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>Marc</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An old weight and coin. See <er>Marc</er>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Lend me a <xex>mark</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The unit of monetary account of the German Empire,
equal to 23.8 cents of United States money (1913); the equivalent of one
hundred pfennigs. Also, a silver coin of this value. The unit was
retained by subsequent German states up to the time of the Federal
Republic of Germany. In 1995, the value was approximately 65 cents
American. In 1999 it began to be superseded by the Euro as a unit of
currency in Germany and throughout much of the European union.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mark
<hw>Mark</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marke</ets>,
<ets>merke</ets>, AS. <ets>mearc</ets>; akin to D. <ets>merk</ets>, MHG.
<ets>marc</ets>, G. <ets>marke</ets>, Icel. <ets>mark</ets>, Dan.
<ets>m⟦ae⟧rke</ets>; cf. Lith. <ets>margas</ets> party-colored.
⟦root⟧106, 273. Cf. <er>Remark</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A visible
sign or impression made or left upon anything; esp., a line, point,
stamp, figure, or the like, drawn or impressed, so as to attract the
attention and convey some information or intimation; a token; a
trace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord set a <qex>mark</qex> upon Cain, lest any finding him
should kill him.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. iv. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 896 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A character or device put
on an article of merchandise by the maker to show by whom it was made; a
trade-mark.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A character (usually a cross) made
as a substitute for a signature by one who can not write.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mark</qex> of the artisan is found upon the most ancient
fabrics that have come to light.</q> <rj><qau>Knight.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A fixed object serving for guidance, as of a ship, a
traveler, a surveyor, etc.; <as>as, a sea<ex>mark</ex>, a
land<ex>mark</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A trace, dot, line, imprint, or discoloration,
although not regarded as a token or sign; a scratch, scar, stain, etc.;
<as>as, this pencil makes a fine <ex>mark</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have some <qex>marks</qex> of yours upon my pate.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An evidence of presence, agency, or influence; a
significative token; a symptom; a trace; specifically, a permanent
impression of one's activity or character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The confusion of tongues was a <qex>mark</qex> of separation.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>That toward which a missile is directed; a thing
aimed at; what one seeks to hit or reach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>France was a fairer <qex>mark</qex> to shoot at than Ireland.</q>
<rj><qau>Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whate'er the motive, pleasure is the <qex>mark</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Attention, regard, or respect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As much in mock as <qex>mark</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Limit or standard of action or fact; <as>as, to be
within the <ex>mark</ex>; to come up to the
<ex>mark</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Badge or sign of honor, rank, or official
station.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the official <qex>marks</qex> invested, you⟦br⟧
Anon do meet the Senate.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Preeminence; high position; <as>as, patricians of
<ex>mark</ex>; a fellow of no <ex>mark</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>A characteristic or essential
attribute; a differential.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>A number or other character used in registering;
<as>as, examination <ex>marks</ex>; a <ex>mark</ex> for
tardiness.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>Image; likeness; hence, those formed in one's
image; children; descendants.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧All the
<xex>mark</xex> of Adam.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>One of the bits of leather or
colored bunting which are placed upon a sounding line at intervals of
from two to five fathoms. The unmarked fathoms are called
⟦ldquo⟧deeps.⟦rdquo⟧</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A man of mark</b></col>, <cd>a conspicuous or eminent
man.</cd> -- <col><b>To make one's mark</b></col>. <fld>(a)</fld> <cd>To
sign, as a letter or other writing, by making a cross or other
mark.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To make a distinct or lasting impression on
the public mind, or on affairs; to gain distinction.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Impress; impression; stamp; print; trace;
vestige; track; characteristic; evidence; proof; token; badge;
indication; symptom.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mark
<hw>Mark</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marked</conjf> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧rkt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>marken</ets>, <ets>merken</ets>, AS. <ets>mearcian</ets>, from
<ets>mearc</ets>. See <er>Mark</er> the sign.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
put a mark upon; to affix a significant mark to; to make recognizable by
a mark; <as>as, to <ex>mark</ex> a box or bale of merchandise; to
<ex>mark</ex> clothing.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be a mark upon; to designate; to indicate; --
used literally and figuratively; <as>as, this monument <ex>marks</ex>
the spot where Wolfe died; his courage and energy <ex>marked</ex> him
for a leader.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To leave a trace, scratch, scar, or other mark,
upon, or any evidence of action; <as>as, a pencil <ex>marks</ex> paper;
his hobnails <ex>marked</ex> the floor.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To keep account of; to enumerate and register;
<as>as, to <ex>mark</ex> the points in a game of billiards or
cards</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To notice or observe; to give attention to; to take
note of; to remark; to heed; to regard; <as>as, <ex>mark</ex> my
words</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Mark</xex> the perfect man.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Ps. xxxvii. 37.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To mark out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To designate, as
by a mark; to select; as, the ringleaders were <xex>marked out</xex> for
punishment</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To obliterate or cancel with a mark;
as, to <xex>mark out</xex> an item in an account.</cd> -- <col><b>To
mark time</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to keep the time of a
marching step by moving the legs alternately without
advancing.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To note; remark; notice; observe; regard; heed;
show; evince; indicate; point out; betoken; denote; characterize; stamp;
imprint; impress; brand.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mark
<hw>Mark</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take particular notice; to
observe critically; to note; to remark.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mark</qex>, I pray you, and see how this man seeketh
mischief.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xx. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markable</ent>⟦br⟧
